'''Reception''', '''Year 0''', '''Nursery''', or '''FS2''' ('''foundation second year''') is the first year of [[primary school]] in the [[United Kingdom]] (except [[Northern Ireland]] and [[Scotland]]). It comes after [[nursery school|nursery]] and before [[Year One (School)|Year One]] in [[England]]<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/national-curriculum/overview|title=The national curriculum - GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|access-date=2016-03-27}}</ref> and [[Wales]] or [[Primary education#Northern Ireland|Primary 2]] in [[Northern Ireland]].
Pupils in Reception are usually aged between four and five.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foundationyears.org.uk/school-reception-class/|title=School reception class - From pregnancy to children aged 5|website=www.foundationyears.org.uk|access-date=2016-03-27}}</ref> Children start school either in the term or in the year in which they reach four,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kent.gov.uk/education-and-children/schools/school-age|title=School age|website=www.kent.gov.uk|access-date=2016-03-27}}</ref> depending on the policy of the [[Local Education Authority]]. Reception is the final part of the [[Foundation Stage|Early Years Foundation Stage]] of education.<ref name=":0" />
Most areas admit entire year groups in September, regardless of which month they were born, meaning that some pupils will be starting primary school in the month of their four birthday, while others will be almost a year ahead of this milestone.
Other areas admit Reception pupils in the term of their fourth birthday, while some admit pupils in September if they were born between September and February, and in January if they were born between March and August.
There is no reception year in [[Scotland]] as children progress directly from Nursery to Primary 1 (equivalent to English Year 1) in the August nearest their fifth birthday. Generally this means that a complete intake into P1 ranges from four and a half to five and a half years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/parentzone/mychild/transitions/startingschool/index.asp|title=Starting school - Transitions -|website=www.educationscotland.gov.uk|access-date=2016-03-27}}</ref> It is also possible for parents of children born in January and February to defer admission by one year, so that they start at five and a half rather than four and a half. {| class="wikitable" |+Early year groups in the UK !England & Wales !Scotland !Northern Ireland !Age |- |Reception |Nursery |P1 |4-5 |- |Year One |Primary 1 |P2 |5-6 |- |Year Two |Primary 2 |P3 |6-7 |} Previously, children in England and Wales had started school later than children in Northern Ireland, where the starting age was generally four, dependent on the date of the child's birthday.
